rComments: Very boring class and instructor. Who knew Plautus was so "unfunny."

I was very excited to take a course focusing on ancient novels, but Gunderson managed to quickly ruin that for me. His lectures were boring and inconsistent, the tests and in-class essays were way too specific to be able to prepare for them. Unfair marker as well. I walked away with an okay grade, but the lectures were torture.

Worst lecturer ever! None of his lectures have anything to do with his evaluations. The "quiz" (worth 30% of the final grade, 1 percent for each question) are random, obscure questions from lengthy readings. There is no way of preparing for this! In class essay is also based solely on the readings. The final? A mixture of the two. Waste of life.

I had prof. Gunderson several years ago for his Sexuality in Antiquity course. He was thorough, friendly and interested in class discussion (though we, myself included, were regrettably quiet). He provided great feedback on essays, and was always very understanding and helpful.
His lectures are so impossibly boring. Half the time he just reads or summarizes the readings. I would advise doing the readings, looking at his online notes, and skipping class.

One of the most utterly useless and poorly taught classes I have ever attended. No over-arching themes or lecture just skimming through the readings. He seems to be more interested in talking to himself then the students. Take CLA232 with Professor Wohl if you want to see how a course like this should be taught.
